<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM MOVIES</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25  2:50:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My name's Craig Reubens.  I was a LTjg with SeaBee Battalion 121,, stationed at Gia Le, &quot;I&quot; Corps, RVN, in 1968-9.<br>
I made it through my tour of duty ostensibly intact, mentally and physically.  I was even able to watch Deer Hunter, Full Metal Jacket, Platoon, 84 Charlie MoPic, Coming Home, and Apocalypse Now, in a normal manner, like most other moviegoers. <br>
However, when I went to see Oliver Stone's third film of his VN trilogy, HEAVEN AND EARTH, I  &quot;met my Waterloo,&quot; to coin a phrase...  Somewhere around a third of the way into the film, I recalled seeing a young Vietnamese boy with one of his legs blown off.  Well, this scene absolutely forced me to recollect another very, very similar young Vietnamese boy whom I'd known in Gia Le, a friendly South Vietnamese son of one of the indigenous workers on our base.  We also blew off one of HIS legs, too.  <br>
Well, at that point, seeing more clearly than ever before the deep and utter senselessness of that war, and the countless horrible tragedies that occurred there, represented by the missing little boy's legs, I started BAWLING.  Right there in the theatre.  And as far as I could tell, I was the only one.  At least the only one as loud as I was - 'cause I wan't just weeping, nor crying softly, I was bawling louder than I'd ever bawled in my life.  And I simply couldn't stop for just about the entire rest of the film.  In fact, I kept bawling right on into the parking lot.  I actually felt embarassed to have made so much noise, but you know what?  I just couldn't stop, and I couldn't (or at least I didn't want to) leave the theater and miss the rest of the film.  Well, that's all, folks.  Just thought you might like to know...
